# CSS Conventions

## Structure

All styles live in `src/global.css`. No CSS modules, no scoped styles. The file is sectioned with comment headers:

```css
/* ===== SECTION NAME ===== */
```

Sections in order: resets/desktop, icons, window overrides, taskbar/start menu, notepad, explorer, photo viewer, browser (IE5), browser pages, context menu, shutdown, responsive.

## Naming

BEM-like convention matching 98.css patterns:

- Block: `.desktop-icon`, `.browser-toolbar`, `.ctx-menu`
- Element: `.desktop-icon__label`, `.bp__hero`, `.ctx-menu__item`
- Modifier: `.desktop-icon--selected`, `.bp__hero--linkedin`, `.ctx-menu__item--bold`

## Key Patterns

- `98.css` provides base Win98 widgets (buttons, windows, title bars, scrollbars, status bars)
- Override with higher specificity when needed: `.win95-window .title-bar { ... }`
- Windows ME look: `#d4d0c8` backgrounds, `#0a246a` blue accents, `Tahoma` and `MS Sans Serif` fonts
- The browser pages (`.bp` block) use `"Times New Roman"` for that early-web feel
- Use `border: 2px outset / inset #d4d0c8` for raised/sunken 3D effects
- Use `box-shadow: 2px 2px 6px rgba(0,0,0,.35)` sparingly for floating elements
